Project Overview¶

This project aims to predict whether a customer will subscribe to a term deposit using the Bank Marketing dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository. We will apply machine learning techniques to analyze the data, build predictive models, and evaluate their performance.

Dataset Source: UCI Repository - Bank Marketing Dataset

Objectives¶

  • Perform Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  • Preprocess the data
  • Train machine learning models
  • Compare model performance
  • Visualize key insights and predictions

Machine Learning Models Used¶

  • Logistic Regression
  • Random Forest
  • XGBoost

#  Function to plot the count and the percentage distribution of 'y' for each category

def plot_y_distribution_categorical(df, feature, xticks_rotation=0, xticks_ha='center'):
  # Count occurrences of 'y' for each feature category
  y_distribution_count = df.groupby(feature)['y'].value_counts().unstack()  # Absolute count
  y_distribution_percentage = df.groupby(feature)['y'].value_counts(normalize=True).unstack() * 100  # Convert to percentage

  # Plot the absolute count of 'y' for each 'unknown_count' category
  plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
  y_distribution_count.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=["royalblue", "gold"])

  # Add total labels on top of each bar group
  for index, value in enumerate(y_distribution_count.sum(axis=1)):
      plt.text(index, value + 200, str(int(value)), ha='center', fontsize=10)

  plt.xlabel(f"{feature}", fontsize=12)
  plt.ylabel("Count of Rows", fontsize=12)
  plt.title(f"distribution of 'y' count based on {feature}", fontsize=14)
  plt.legend(title="Subscription Outcome (y)", loc="upper right", bbox_to_anchor=(1.4, 1))
  plt.xticks(rotation=xticks_rotation, ha=xticks_ha)
  plt.show()

  # Plot the percentage distribution of 'y' for each 'job' category
  plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
  y_distribution_percentage.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=["royalblue", "gold"])

  # Add percentage labels on top of each bar group if percentage > 0%
  for bars in plt.gca().containers:
      for bar in bars:
          height = bar.get_height()
          if height > 0:
              plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_y() + height / 2, f"{height:.1f}%", ha='center', fontsize=8, color='black')

  plt.xlabel(f"{feature}", fontsize=12)
  plt.ylabel("Percentage (%)", fontsize=12)
  plt.title(f"distribution of 'y' percentage based on {feature}", fontsize=14)
  plt.legend(title="Subscription Outcome (y)", loc="upper right", bbox_to_anchor=(1.4, 1))
  plt.xticks(rotation=xticks_rotation, ha=xticks_ha)
  plt.show()

Identify Categorical and Numerical Features¶

Removal of input features¶

In [23]:
# 1. Drop 'duration' column
# Notes from bank-additional-names.txt:
### This attribute highly affects the output target (e.g., if duration=0 then y="no").
### Yet, the duration is not known before a call is performed. Also, after the end of the call y is obviously known.
### Thus, this input should only be included for benchmark purposes and should be discarded if the intention is to have a realistic predictive model.
df.drop(['duration'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# For Logistic Regression only
# 2. Drop euribor3m and emp.var.rate to reduce multicollienarity
df_logreg = df.copy()
df_logreg.drop(['euribor3m', 'emp.var.rate'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Logistic Regression (Feature Importance)¶

❗ If you want to try to drop columns to see any model improvement can use feature importance to drop low importance features. Else, if not using can remove this section.

*How to read SHAP?*

Y-Axis: Features Ranked by Importance

Features are sorted by importance (top = most influential). Most important feature: nr.employed Least influential among shown features: marital_married

X-Axis: SHAP Value (Impact on Model Output)

Negative SHAP value → Decreases the likelihood of predicting the positive class (y = 1).

Positive SHAP value → Increases the likelihood of predicting the positive class (y = 1). The further from zero, the stronger the impact.

Color: Feature Value

Red = High feature value (e.g., high nr.employed or previous count).

Blue = Low feature value (e.g., low pdays).

Random Forest (Fine Tuning)¶

We need to use class_weight balanced in this case because of the imbalance dataset.

The majority class will get a higher weight while minority will get lower weight. This forces the model to pay more attention to the minority class.

Performance Evaluation¶

In [60]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics import (
    accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score,
    f1_score, roc_auc_score, classification_report
)

# Define function to extract classification metrics
def get_classification_metrics(y_true, y_pred, model, proba_pred=None):
    report = classification_report(y_true, y_pred, output_dict=True)

    # Get Precision & Recall separately for Yes & No
    precision_no = report["False"]["precision"]
    precision_yes = report["True"]["precision"]
    recall_no = report["False"]["recall"]
    recall_yes = report["True"]["recall"]

    metrics = {
        "Accuracy": accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "Precision - No": precision_no,
        "Precision - Yes": precision_yes,
        "Recall - No": recall_no,
        "Recall - Yes": recall_yes,
        "F1-Score": f1_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "AUC-ROC": roc_auc_score(y_true, proba_pred[:, 1]) if proba_pred is not None else None
    }
    return metrics

# Store results for baseline models
baseline_results = {
    "Logistic Regression": get_classification_metrics(logreg_y_test, logreg_y_test_pred, logreg, logreg.predict_proba(logreg_X_test)),
    "Random Forest": get_classification_metrics(rf_y_test, rf_y_pred, rf_model, rf_model.predict_proba(rf_X_test)),
    "XGBoost": get_classification_metrics(y_test, xgb_y_test_pred, xgb, xgb.predict_proba(X_test))
}

# Store results for fine-tuned models
tuned_results = {
    "Logistic Regression": get_classification_metrics(logreg_y_test, best_logreg_y_test_pred, best_logreg, best_logreg.predict_proba(logreg_X_test)),
    "Random Forest": get_classification_metrics(rf_y_test, best_rf_y_test_pred_test, best_rf, best_rf.predict_proba(rf_X_test)),
    "XGBoost": get_classification_metrics(y_test, best_xgb_y_test_pred, xgb_rs, xgb_rs.predict_proba(X_test))
}

# Convert to DataFrames for visualization
df_baseline = pd.DataFrame(baseline_results)
df_tuned = pd.DataFrame(tuned_results)

# Function to plot each metric separately in 1x1 layout
def plot_metrics(df, title_prefix):
    metrics_to_plot = ["Accuracy", "Precision - No", "Precision - Yes", "Recall - No", "Recall - Yes", "F1-Score", "AUC-ROC"]

    for metric in metrics_to_plot:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))  # Large full-size figure for each plot
        ax = plt.gca()  # Get current axis
        bars = df.loc[metric].plot(kind="bar", ax=ax, color=["blue", "green", "red"])

        # Set x-axis labels to show model names only
        ax.set_xticklabels(df.columns, rotation=0)

        # Add numbers on top of bars
        for bar in bars.patches:
            height = bar.get_height()
            ax.text(
                bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2,  # X-coordinate (center of the bar)
                height,  # Position ABOVE the bar
                f"{height:.3f}",  # Format to 3 decimal places
                ha="center", va="bottom", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold", color="black"
            )

        # Set titles and labels
        ax.set_title(f"{title_prefix} {metric} Comparison", fontsize=16, pad=15)  # Better spacing
        ax.set_ylabel("Score", fontsize=14)
        ax.set_ylim(0, 1.02)  # Ensure full-scale view
        ax.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()  # Show one plot at a time

# Plot Baseline and Fine-Tuned Model Performance (1-by-1 graphs)
plot_metrics(df_baseline, "Baseline")
plot_metrics(df_tuned, "Fine-Tuned")

# Preprocessing

# Remove leading/trailing spaces from column names
df_manual.columns = df_manual.columns.str.strip()

# List of categorical columns to one-hot encode (same as training data)
categorical_cols = [
    "job", "marital", "education", "default", "housing", "loan",
    "contact", "month", "day_of_week", "poutcome"
]

# One-hot encode categorical variables
df_manual = pd.get_dummies(df_manual, columns=categorical_cols, drop_first=False)

# Expected columns from the trained model
expected_columns = [
    'age', 'campaign', 'pdays', 'previous', 'emp.var.rate', 'cons.price.idx',
    'cons.conf.idx', 'euribor3m', 'nr.employed', 'job_admin.', 'job_blue-collar',
    'job_entrepreneur', 'job_housemaid', 'job_management', 'job_retired',
    'job_self-employed', 'job_services', 'job_student', 'job_technician',
    'job_unemployed', 'job_unknown', 'marital_divorced', 'marital_married',
    'marital_single', 'marital_unknown', 'education_basic.4y',
    'education_basic.6y', 'education_basic.9y', 'education_high.school',
    'education_illiterate', 'education_professional.course',
    'education_university.degree', 'education_unknown', 'default_no',
    'default_unknown', 'default_yes', 'housing_no', 'housing_unknown',
    'housing_yes', 'loan_no', 'loan_unknown', 'loan_yes', 'contact_cellular',
    'contact_telephone', 'month_apr', 'month_aug', 'month_dec', 'month_jul',
    'month_jun', 'month_mar', 'month_may', 'month_nov', 'month_oct',
    'month_sep', 'day_of_week_fri', 'day_of_week_mon', 'day_of_week_thu',
    'day_of_week_tue', 'day_of_week_wed', 'poutcome_failure',
    'poutcome_nonexistent', 'poutcome_success'
]

# Ensure all expected columns exist, filling missing ones with 0
for col in expected_columns:
    if col not in df_manual.columns:
        df_manual[col] = False

# Keep only expected columns
df_manual = df_manual[expected_columns]

# Scaling Numeric Features with the **same saved scaler**
numerical_cols = ['age', 'campaign', 'pdays', 'previous', 'emp.var.rate',
                  'cons.price.idx', 'cons.conf.idx', 'euribor3m', 'nr.employed']

df_manual[numerical_cols] = scaler.transform(df_manual[numerical_cols])
